design for 10-year-olds.

00:02:19.370 --> 00:02:22.520
And so when you think about
it, the future generations

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:24.890
are really the
design assignment.

00:02:24.890 --> 00:02:26.600
And it's a great
pleasure and a privilege

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:29.510
to be able to work toward
those children and their health

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:30.410
and their joys.

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:32.420
So that's really the optimism.

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:34.550
It's to make the
world better for them.

00:02:34.550 --> 00:02:37.180
Now, as an architect the
first job of an architect

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:39.140
is to change the way you see.

00:02:39.140 --> 00:02:41.220
Then we rearrange furniture.

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:42.260
Then we build.

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:44.540
So start by changing
the way you see.

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:49.360
This poem by Hildegarde
Von Bingen from 1124--

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:52.970
"glance at the sun, see
the moon and the stars,

00:02:52.970 --> 00:02:55.410
gaze at the beauty
of earth's greenings.

00:02:55.410 --> 00:02:57.530
Now, think."

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:00.590
This is a really
important set of phrases

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:09.077
because, glance, see, gaze,
think is really important,

00:03:09.077 --> 00:03:10.910
especially when we
realize what a delight it

00:03:10.910 --> 00:03:15.680
is to be here on this planet
in the natural context.

00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:19.640
But this last
section concerns me

00:03:19.640 --> 00:03:25.340
because the language we use here
can be so sadly interpreted.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:29.450
All nature is at the
disposal of humankind.

00:03:29.450 --> 00:03:32.390
We are to work with it for
without it we cannot survive.

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:36.830
This is what translates
into sustainability.

00:03:36.830 --> 00:03:39.530
I won the presidential award
for sustainable development

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:42.170
from President Clinton in 1996.

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:47.060
And we were in the ceremony,
and one of the reporters

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:50.510
came up and said,
Mr. Sustainable,

00:03:50.510 --> 00:03:52.470
what does it all mean?

00:03:52.470 --> 00:03:54.740
And I remember looking
at him and saying,

00:03:54.740 --> 00:03:57.910
I'm not that really
interested in sustainability.

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:00.320
What's your relationship
to your spouse?

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:04.980
If you say, sustainable,
I'd say, I'm sorry.

00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:06.880
It sounds kind of boring really.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:08.170
What is this, maintenance?

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:11.530
So it's really important to
look at this these phrases

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:14.920
because this is about a
concept known as usufruct.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:18.000
It's the idea that things
are there for our use.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:18.500
Right?

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:19.930
And they're there for our use.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:22.060
But if you go to
native peoples, they

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:25.444
talk about being in relation
with the natural world.

00:04:25.444 --> 00:04:26.860
And that's really
I think what I'd

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:30.770
like to talk about today--
use, but also relationships.

00:04:30.770 --> 00:04:34.600
So I see us all as designers
because we all have intentions.

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:38.956
And design is the first
signal of human intention.

00:04:38.956 --> 00:04:40.330
So when you get
up in the morning

00:04:40.330 --> 00:04:43.300
you have intentions to make
Google more sustainable here

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:44.060
in New York.

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:44.560
Right.

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:45.980
You have intentions
every morning,

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:47.860
and then you have to go out
there and see how well you're

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:50.318
doing against those, and try
to get everybody else to align

00:04:50.318 --> 00:04:51.920
with your intentions.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:54.580
So I think design is intention.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:04:58.119
And so what is our intention,
to make the world a worse place?

00:04:58.119 --> 00:05:00.160
Anybody got that when they
get up in the morning?

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:03.967
Like, I'm going to get out
there and do something worse.

00:05:03.967 --> 00:05:05.050
It's hard to imagine that.

00:05:05.050 --> 00:05:06.160
Really?

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:08.980
I'm sure there are people
who are doing that,

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:11.620
but perhaps not intentionally.

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:13.130
So that becomes a question.

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:15.580
How about, let's get out
there and be less bad?

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:17.270
Oh, really?

00:05:17.270 --> 00:05:19.120
See, being less bad
is not being good.

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:23.140
It's being bad by
definition, just less so.

00:05:23.140 --> 00:05:27.779
So let's get out there
and be bad, just less so.

00:05:27.779 --> 00:05:29.070
It's hard to imagine, isn't it?

00:05:29.070 --> 00:05:30.850
But that's what we do.

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:34.060
So let's start with where
we are and see if we

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:35.380
can see something different.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:38.730
So for me, I was born
in Tokyo in 1951.

00:05:38.730 --> 00:05:42.674
And as a baby we would wake
up in the middle of the night.

00:05:42.674 --> 00:05:44.340
We lived in a traditional
Japanese house

00:05:44.340 --> 00:05:45.630
with paper walls.

00:05:45.630 --> 00:05:47.580
And we would hear
the farmers coming in

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:49.680
to collect our
sewage to take back

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:52.590
to the farms with their
oxcarts on the cobblestones.

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:53.409
They'd wake us up.

00:05:53.409 --> 00:05:55.200
And my mother would
come in and put us back

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.560
to sleep by singing
folk songs from Alabama

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:01.530
with her southern accent
in Japanese with words

00:06:01.530 --> 00:06:05.160
she was making up that
had to do with poop.

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:07.170
And it was about
the honey wagons

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:09.684
coming to collect the night
soil to take it to the farms

00:06:09.684 --> 00:06:11.100
to bring us our
food the next day.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:12.960
And you're three years
old, and your mother

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:16.410
is singing poop
songs in Japanese

00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:18.020
with a southern accent.

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:19.530
Anyway, heaven.

00:06:19.530 --> 00:06:21.360
So there it was.

00:06:21.360 --> 00:06:25.830
So I always thought the cities
and the farms are one organism.

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:28.830
But I also became
aware of Hiroshima,

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:34.350
because I was five years old
when I discovered Hiroshima.

00:06:34.350 --> 00:06:36.510
And it started with a
picture in Life Magazine.

00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:38.850
And I looked at it I
said, what is this?

00:06:38.850 --> 00:06:42.270
And they said, this is war.

00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:44.707
War is when we
kill the children.

00:06:44.707 --> 00:06:47.040
So what I'm looking at here
is the idea of waging peace.

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:49.689
And so when I got to college,
I went to the physics professor

00:06:49.689 --> 00:06:52.230
and I said, how do you make a
city disappear in five seconds?

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:55.500
It takes thousands of years
to make things and seconds

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:56.940
to destroy them.

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:58.080
Building is slow.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:00.120
Destruction is fast.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:01.192
How is that possible?

00:07:01.192 --> 00:07:03.150
And he gave me the special
theory of relativity

00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:04.800
and said here, read this.

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:05.715
Solve this equation.

00:07:05.715 --> 00:07:07.160
E equals mc squared.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.760
All right, you're
all smart people.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:10.650
Have you all solved
E equals mc squared?

00:07:10.650 --> 00:07:12.011
Anybody here?

00:07:12.011 --> 00:07:12.510
Ha.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:13.530
What to do it?

00:07:13.530 --> 00:07:15.630
Why not.

00:07:15.630 --> 00:07:17.520
If you ask the question,
how does a city

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:19.290
disappear, all of
a sudden it starts

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:20.970
to look a little
different, because c

00:07:20.970 --> 00:07:22.300
is the number in the constant.

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:25.060
So that's to me almost
infinity, because it's bigger

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:26.270
than I can imagine--

00:07:26.270 --> 00:07:27.172
the light and then.

00:07:27.172 --> 00:07:29.380
And then square it, just in
case it's not big enough.

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:29.879
All right.

00:07:29.879 --> 00:07:32.250
So call it almost
infinity squared.

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:33.030
Oh boy.

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:36.330
And then that means that if m
is in any way a positive number,

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:40.530
as in one hydrogen atom,
then the e is almost infinity

00:07:40.530 --> 00:07:41.670
squared.

00:07:41.670 --> 00:07:44.584
That is the atom bomb.

00:07:44.584 --> 00:07:47.860
There it is-- nuclear power.

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:49.710
But, if we then
look at the planet

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:51.880
we realize that that's
coming from the sun,

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:54.810
and it hits the earth, which
is materials and water--

00:07:54.810 --> 00:07:56.552
mass, m.

00:07:56.552 --> 00:07:59.010
And Einstein was really dealing
with physics and chemistry.

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:00.630
Isn't that interesting?

00:08:00.630 --> 00:08:03.265
But who are we?

00:08:03.265 --> 00:08:05.030
See, we are not
physics and chemistry.

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:07.990
We're what happened when
those two things get together.

00:08:07.990 --> 00:08:09.600
We're biology.

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:11.660
And so it's interesting
to note in Latin

00:08:11.660 --> 00:08:15.190
that the roots for these
three words are the same--

00:08:15.190 --> 00:08:20.850
humous, human, humility.

00:08:20.850 --> 00:08:24.290
To be humble is to be grounded.

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:25.400
Isn't that something?

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:26.910
We are of the soil.

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:29.570
So Francis Crick
printed out, nine years

00:08:29.570 --> 00:08:32.690
after discovering DNA at
Cambridge with James Watson,

00:08:32.690 --> 00:08:34.400
that in order to
be a living thing

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:38.840
you have to have growth,
because otherwise you're dying.

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:41.794
If you have more cells dying
than growing, you're dying.

00:08:41.794 --> 00:08:44.210
So you have to have income if
you've going to have growth.

00:08:44.210 --> 00:08:45.720
And income comes from the sun.

00:08:45.720 --> 00:08:49.190
It comes from carbon from
the atmosphere and nitrogen

00:08:49.190 --> 00:08:50.270
from the atmosphere.

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:53.300
And you have to have an
open metabolism of chemicals

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:55.490
operating for the
benefit of the organisms

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:57.570
and their reproduction.

00:08:57.570 --> 00:09:00.200
So, here we go.

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:03.080
So I thought, well, what if
we could design with this?

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:05.750
So let's first start
by saying, what

00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:07.640
is going with all this
eco-efficiency stuff?

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:12.020
We're all trying to be less
bad, and think I'm being good.

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:13.370
So let's have a goal.

00:09:13.370 --> 00:09:15.044
Let's make a less
bad goal and see

00:09:15.044 --> 00:09:17.210
how excited you are about
getting up in the morning.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:18.159
Let's be optimistic.

00:09:18.159 --> 00:09:19.575
We're going to
make a world that's

00:09:19.575 --> 00:09:22.370
less unsafe, less unhealthy,
less unjust, with less

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:25.790
polluted air, less polluted
soil, water, and power,

00:09:25.790 --> 00:09:26.900
and economically driven.

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:28.100
How are we doing?

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:28.670
Is this it?

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:30.850
Get up in the morning,
go get it done.

00:09:30.850 --> 00:09:31.549
Right?

00:09:31.549 --> 00:09:32.840
Whereas you know how to search.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:35.210
Why don't you just search for
this. a delightfully diverse,

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:36.560
safe, healthy, and just world--

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.050
with clean air, soil, water,
and power-- economically,

00:09:39.050 --> 00:09:42.820
equitably, ecologically,
and elegantly enjoyed.

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:44.610
There.

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:49.310
So, if all we do
is report as we see

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:51.600
in so many corporate
sustainability

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:58.470
reporting and corporate social
responsibility reporting,

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:00.420
we see all these
charts like this, even

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:02.530
with carbon dioxide emissions.

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:07.540
It's like, I'm going to reduce
my emissions by 20% by 2020,

00:10:07.540 --> 00:10:09.640
and my goal is zero.

00:10:09.640 --> 00:10:13.500
Toxins-- I'm going to reduce
my toxins by 20% by 2020.

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:15.480
My goal is zero.

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:16.230
Really.

00:10:16.230 --> 00:10:17.640
Think about that for a minute.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.026
You're telling the children,
your goal is nothing,

00:10:21.026 --> 00:10:22.650
and they're making
it difficult for you

00:10:22.650 --> 00:10:25.180
to do nothing, because you
have to feed and clothe them.

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:26.400
That's not too exciting.

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:30.516
And then you're telling us
what you're not going to do.

00:10:30.516 --> 00:10:32.640
That would be like me
jumping in a taxi and saying,

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:36.490
quick, I'm not going
to the airport.

00:10:36.490 --> 00:10:40.260
Is this really useful,
what we're not going to do?

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.480
So, what if we
take this and say,

00:10:42.480 --> 00:10:44.460
let's not make that
on the top chart.

00:10:44.460 --> 00:10:46.300
Let's put that
underneath, and say,

00:10:46.300 --> 00:10:50.360
what we don't want we put below,
what we do want we put above.

00:10:50.360 --> 00:10:53.310
And let's just imagine
having zero of the bads

00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:55.860
and 100% of the goods.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:11:00.010
We talk about selling
goods and services.

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:02.730
Well, what if you've actually
thought about it and said,

00:11:02.730 --> 00:11:04.650
I sell bads.

00:11:04.650 --> 00:11:08.060
Today I'm going to
try to sell less bads.

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:10.166
We call them goods.

00:11:10.166 --> 00:11:11.790
And then we also
realize this year, I'm

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:14.070
sure you're aware, that
most of the economy

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:16.690
is actually trading,
and the amount that's

00:11:16.690 --> 00:11:19.740
in goods and services is
actually probably about 20%.

00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:22.560
The rest of its arbitrage and
fooling around with numbers.

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:26.190
So the actual basis of the
economy is a small part of it,

00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:28.890
but it's fundamental because
it's the context in which we

00:11:28.890 --> 00:11:29.940
have life.

00:11:29.940 --> 00:11:32.100
So our choices-- are we
designing for the top part

00:11:32.100 --> 00:11:32.766
of this picture.

00:11:32.766 --> 00:11:35.190
Are we designing for the
bottom part of this picture?

00:11:35.190 --> 00:11:37.600
So that's the question.

00:11:37.600 --> 00:11:38.370
So let's go do it.

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:39.960
What is design for good?

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:43.240
So the sustainable development
goals-- there's 17 of them--

00:11:43.240 --> 00:11:44.740
have been put forward
by the UN now.

00:11:44.740 --> 00:11:47.670
They're much, I think, better
than the former millennial

00:11:47.670 --> 00:11:49.220
goals because
they're quite precise

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:50.220
and they're quite clear.

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:52.110
And there's nothing here
I think anybody here

00:11:52.110 --> 00:11:54.480
would say is not a good idea.

00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:56.860
And let us know if you think so.

00:11:56.860 --> 00:11:59.439
And the circular economy is
certainly an important one,

00:11:59.439 --> 00:12:00.480
but it's just right here.

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:01.200
It's number 12.

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:02.360
It's one.

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:04.630
But a lot of business
people, when they say,

00:12:04.630 --> 00:12:06.790
oh 17 goals, how
can do all that?

00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:08.250
Well you can actually.

00:12:08.250 --> 00:12:09.180
And I'll show you now.

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:10.638
And will cradle to
cradle thinking,

00:12:10.638 --> 00:12:13.793
if you do material health,
circular economy, material

00:12:13.793 --> 00:12:17.730
re-utilization, renewable
energy, water stewardship,

00:12:17.730 --> 00:12:21.450
and social fairness, you
can do all 17 at once.

00:12:21.450 --> 00:12:23.760
But it's not going to help
us, for example, to have

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:27.630
a circular economy circulating
bads, because all you're doing

00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:29.840
is recirculating the bads.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.020
If you have toxic products
and you recirculate them,

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:33.285
you retoxify.

00:12:33.285 --> 00:12:35.700
So you're putting the "re"
back into the resource.

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:38.460
But what if the source is toxic?

00:12:38.460 --> 00:12:40.080
Just remember, a
toxin is a material

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:42.510
in the wrong place, the wrong
dose, the wrong duration.

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:44.400
Water is highly toxic.

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:48.690
If I surround you with this
for six minutes, you're dead.

00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:51.090
If you jump out of an
airplane and hit the ocean

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:56.130
at terminal velocity, very, very
short duration, very big dose--

00:12:56.130 --> 00:12:56.830
you're dead.

00:12:56.830 --> 00:12:59.940
So materials in the wrong place,
wrong dose, wrong duration

00:12:59.940 --> 00:13:00.540
are toxic.

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:03.030
We don't say to the
children of Flint,

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:08.730
we're going to reduce the lead
in your water by 20% by 2020.

00:13:08.730 --> 00:13:11.730
When you have a toxin, you stop.

00:13:11.730 --> 00:13:13.160
You stop.

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:15.380
So starting in 1992, working
with Michael Braungart,

00:13:15.380 --> 00:13:19.020
a chemist, we created
criteria that we use.

00:13:19.020 --> 00:13:20.910
No more cancer,
no more disruption

00:13:20.910 --> 00:13:22.860
of endocrine systems,
genetic mutations,

00:13:22.860 --> 00:13:25.200
reproductive toxicities,
and birth defects.

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:27.030
Why can't we design these out?

00:13:27.030 --> 00:13:29.880
Precautionary principle-- if
it could cause that problem,

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:31.050
why have it?

00:13:31.050 --> 00:13:31.660
Just move on.

00:13:31.660 --> 00:13:33.510
Don't argue about
the little doses.

00:13:33.510 --> 00:13:35.490
Talk about getting rid of it.

00:13:35.490 --> 00:13:37.530
We looked at environmental
criteria-- toxicity

00:13:37.530 --> 00:13:41.160
for fish, for vertebrates,
invertebrates, plants.

00:13:41.160 --> 00:13:44.450
We looked at toxic heavy
metals, persistence and so on.

00:13:44.450 --> 00:13:46.950
And then we want to know where
it comes from, where it goes,

00:13:46.950 --> 00:13:50.230
how's it being managed,
how does it affect people?

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:52.260
So we developed a
certification program

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:54.170
which is now in
the public domain

00:13:54.170 --> 00:13:56.010
for constant improvement--

00:13:56.010 --> 00:14:00.020
third-party, independent,
peer reviewed.

00:14:00.020 --> 00:14:02.860
And this is what we shared
with Google as well.

00:14:02.860 --> 00:14:04.800
So in this search for
the good, let's just

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:06.485
keep it simple for the kids.

00:14:06.485 --> 00:14:07.980
All right?

00:14:07.980 --> 00:14:11.890
Good, clean water is good.

00:14:11.890 --> 00:14:14.610
Dirty water is bad.

00:14:14.610 --> 00:14:16.620
So when you think
about trying to deal

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:21.300
with platonic perfections
of truth, beauty,

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:31.530
and equity, and rights, and the
humanism of our relationships,

00:14:31.530 --> 00:14:35.790
morals, ethics, you can
talk about the good.

00:14:35.790 --> 00:14:38.790
If you look at Aristotelian
science and math

00:14:38.790 --> 00:14:42.240
and statistical significance,
which Google obviously

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:47.040
is a part and a practitioner
of statistical significance,

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:49.920
then you've got the math.

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:50.950
Right.

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:53.650
So if we try and
put this together,

00:14:53.650 --> 00:14:55.560
we realize to start
with the good.

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:57.120
It's easier than
right and wrong,

00:14:57.120 --> 00:15:01.310
because right and wrong lead us
to politics and other things.

00:15:01.310 --> 00:15:02.560
Good and bad are pretty basic.

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:05.430
So let's say if we have good
materials, good economy,

00:15:05.430 --> 00:15:09.030
good energy, good water, and
good lives, what would we do?

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:11.670
So good materials would
be safe, healthy for

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:13.440
ecologically and human systems.

00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:16.740
They would be biological
and technical nutrients.

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:18.120
That would be first--

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:20.040
so things that go
back to nature, things

00:15:20.040 --> 00:15:21.750
that go back to industry.

00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:24.780
What I want from this cup
that we were drinking out

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:26.130
of here that was PLA--

00:15:26.130 --> 00:15:26.880
it's compostable.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:29.220
That can go back to
the biological cycle.

00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:30.870
This is polyester terephthalate.

00:15:30.870 --> 00:15:32.250
This is polyethylene.

00:15:32.250 --> 00:15:34.860
This can go back to
technical material.

00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:38.730
So let's just imagine it that
way-- two nutrient cycles.

00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:40.582
A good economy would
be circular, of course,

00:15:40.582 --> 00:15:42.040
putting the "re"
back in resources,

00:15:42.040 --> 00:15:46.150
but only if the resource
itself is safe and healthy.

00:15:46.150 --> 00:15:48.880
So it's quality
first, then quantity.

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:51.850
Sharing-- Uber, Airbng--

00:15:51.850 --> 00:15:55.120
sharing things that we could use
to get more utility from them

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:56.530
of course is a good idea.

00:15:56.530 --> 00:15:58.591
But finally shared,
because it was pointed out

00:15:58.591 --> 00:16:01.090
at the World Economic Forum
that eight people in this world,

00:16:01.090 --> 00:16:03.190
individuals, six of
whom are American,

00:16:03.190 --> 00:16:06.940
have the equivalent wealth so
three and 1/2 billion people.

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:10.190
The bottom half of
the economic spectrum.

00:16:10.190 --> 00:16:12.870
So is that shared?

00:16:12.870 --> 00:16:14.830
Then we think about
the linear economy.

00:16:14.830 --> 00:16:17.242
And what we do is
take, make, and waste.

00:16:17.242 --> 00:16:18.700
And so as long as
we do that, we're

00:16:18.700 --> 00:16:19.783
going to run out of stuff.

00:16:19.783 --> 00:16:22.420
And everybody worries
about decoupling materials

00:16:22.420 --> 00:16:27.746
from our economy because of the
problems with their connection.

00:16:27.746 --> 00:16:29.620
But if you then put it
in a circular economy,

00:16:29.620 --> 00:16:31.900
we can start to think
about how we might even

00:16:31.900 --> 00:16:34.790
be able to restore the natural
world with an economy that

00:16:34.790 --> 00:16:35.710
reuses.

00:16:35.710 --> 00:16:37.900
So we've been working with
companies like Steelcase,

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:40.244
Herman Miller and
so to design chairs

00:16:40.244 --> 00:16:41.285
that can be disassembled.

00:16:41.285 --> 00:16:42.993
Say a chair like this--
it's very simple.

00:16:42.993 --> 00:16:43.830
It's got a foam.

00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:44.990
It's got a polymer.

00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:46.910
It has a fabric.

00:16:46.910 --> 00:16:50.230
This one I think is a polyester.

00:16:50.230 --> 00:16:53.050
And then you've got
steel, rubber, and so on.

00:16:53.050 --> 00:16:55.133
Now these can be designed
to go back into systems.

00:16:55.133 --> 00:16:55.633
Fine.

00:16:55.633 --> 00:16:57.591
Now we have to figure
out how to get that done.

00:16:57.591 --> 00:16:59.560
We work in the carpet
industry very vigorously.

00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:01.090
What you want from a
carpet, we pointed out,

00:17:01.090 --> 00:17:03.631
is just service of the carpet--
acoustics, appearance, and so

00:17:03.631 --> 00:17:04.310
on.

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:06.520
And if you think of it
as a relationship instead

00:17:06.520 --> 00:17:09.910
of a resource, the carpet
can be sold to the customer,

00:17:09.910 --> 00:17:11.650
but taken back by
the carpet company

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:13.540
as their raw
material in 10 years.

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:16.329
And then we can recycle 1.4
billion pounds of carbon

00:17:16.329 --> 00:17:19.190
material every year and have
a perpetual carbon industry,

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:21.670
if we design it cradle to cradle
and it's safe and healthy,

00:17:21.670 --> 00:17:23.410
and we use renewable
power and so on.

00:17:23.410 --> 00:17:26.170
Change the carpet, the world
gets better, more jobs.

00:17:26.170 --> 00:17:27.126
Good.

00:17:27.126 --> 00:17:28.750
What's really happening
there is you're

00:17:28.750 --> 00:17:32.200
storing your materials on
your customer's floors.

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:35.620
So when we look at
biological nutrition,

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:40.300
we do textiles where we've
done cotton polyesters--

00:17:40.300 --> 00:17:43.270
excuse me, cotton,
wool, ramie and so on.

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:45.550
And we just announced
two weeks ago

00:17:45.550 --> 00:17:49.745
in Amsterdam, the first 100%
of the molecules assessed

00:17:49.745 --> 00:17:53.350
for ecological and human health
t-shirt at a mass market price.

00:17:53.350 --> 00:17:55.240
They're making 1/2
a million of them--

00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:57.280
C&amp;A. It's pretty exciting.

00:17:57.280 --> 00:18:01.850
So 100% of molecules assessed
for ecological human health.

00:18:01.850 --> 00:18:04.360
So the future involves
mining of a different sort.

00:18:04.360 --> 00:18:05.710
This is mining circuit boards.

00:18:05.710 --> 00:18:09.430
If you mine gold out in nature,
it's $210 a ton production.

00:18:09.430 --> 00:18:13.060
If you mine it from
circuit boards from phones,

00:18:13.060 --> 00:18:14.620
it's worth $27,000 a ton.

00:18:14.620 --> 00:18:17.392
And we can get it done
without any contamination.

00:18:17.392 --> 00:18:18.350
It's quite astonishing.

00:18:18.350 --> 00:18:20.980
These factories can
be self-contained.

00:18:20.980 --> 00:18:23.440
When we looked at a washing
machine 25 years ago and said,

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:24.310
it's really a service.

00:18:24.310 --> 00:18:25.351
You want to wash clothes.

00:18:25.351 --> 00:18:28.065
You don't need to own rubber
gaskets and steel and glass,

00:18:28.065 --> 00:18:30.190
everybody said, well you're
a communist because you

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:31.355
don't believe in ownership.

00:18:31.355 --> 00:18:32.980
And we're saying,
well, what do I need?

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:34.210
I mean, think about a building.

00:18:34.210 --> 00:18:36.376
This is a building we
designed for Bosch and Siemens

00:18:36.376 --> 00:18:37.390
who make, guess what?

00:18:37.390 --> 00:18:38.440
Washing machines.

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:39.770
And think of the building.

00:18:39.770 --> 00:18:40.780
It's a showroom.

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:42.040
It's a washing machine.

00:18:42.040 --> 00:18:44.860
It's a giant vessel
with people all over it.

00:18:44.860 --> 00:18:47.620
But the fact is that you can
have these on a 15-year lease.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:50.384
And the materials are valuable
and valuable to the people

00:18:50.384 --> 00:18:51.550
who can use those materials.

00:18:51.550 --> 00:18:52.240
Not you.

00:18:52.240 --> 00:18:53.762
You get to wash the clothes.

00:18:53.762 --> 00:18:54.970
Here you get to work or live.

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:57.880
This building can be converted
to housing in the future.

00:18:57.880 --> 00:18:59.620
In Amsterdam we're
doing a big project

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:01.578
where we look at the
materials and the building

00:19:01.578 --> 00:19:03.790
as assets, perpetual assets.

00:19:03.790 --> 00:19:05.979
So we design them with
our computer coding

00:19:05.979 --> 00:19:07.270
so we know where everything is.

00:19:07.270 --> 00:19:09.632
The steel beam can be
sold as a steel beam

00:19:09.632 --> 00:19:10.840
if the building's taken down.

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:13.570
If you do it this way,
design for disassembly

00:19:13.570 --> 00:19:16.120
with the buildings
as perpetual assets,

00:19:16.120 --> 00:19:19.300
the cost of tearing down
a building in 15 years

00:19:19.300 --> 00:19:21.670
if the bank ends up with it,
to get it out of the way,

00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:23.290
is 80 euros a square meter.

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:26.110
The value of selling it,
if we do it this way,

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.070
is about 120 euros
a square meter.

00:19:28.070 --> 00:19:31.610
So there's a spread of about 200
euros a square meter, about $20

00:19:31.610 --> 00:19:33.970
per square foot, with the
difference of designing

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:34.970
it one way or the other.

00:19:34.970 --> 00:19:38.560
And this attaches itself
to your current pro forma,

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:41.740
because it's a massive risk
reduction for the finance

00:19:41.740 --> 00:19:43.060
community.

00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:44.860
So these buildings
are all designed

00:19:44.860 --> 00:19:47.620
to be converted to
housing in the future.

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:50.450
This is the waste treatment
system for the project right

00:19:50.450 --> 00:19:50.950
here.

00:19:50.950 --> 00:19:53.200
Turn into an asset
instead of a liability.

00:19:53.200 --> 00:19:55.510
Here's a building we
did for IBM that is now

00:19:55.510 --> 00:19:56.749
being converted to housing.

00:19:56.749 --> 00:19:59.290
And the developers called us
and said, we can't believe this.

00:19:59.290 --> 00:20:01.400
We took your floor
plan and it's housing.

00:20:01.400 --> 00:20:03.370
And we said, yeah, we
designed it that way.

00:20:03.370 --> 00:20:05.000
We designed the building
to be converted housing

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:07.210
in the future, just in case
they didn't need offices.

00:20:07.210 --> 00:20:08.350
Why wouldn't we do that?

00:20:08.350 --> 00:20:09.770
How much fun.

