00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:35.460
to west during the
day, and it brings back

00:22:35.460 --> 00:22:38.610
all the grasses, the
agriculture, the water

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:39.750
and the soil.

00:22:39.750 --> 00:22:40.710
It's unbelievable.

00:22:40.710 --> 00:22:42.990
The fungus starts to grow
because of the shade.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.180
And so this idea, I
think, of actually

00:22:45.180 --> 00:22:47.580
being able to do five
economic strains at once--

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:54.990
fiber, food, water retention,
carbon sequestration,

00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:58.860
atmospheric cooling,
and solar energy,

00:22:58.860 --> 00:23:00.750
and actually the
production of clean water

00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:03.240
because we can use them as
dew collectors in the morning

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:06.160
and then use it as focused
irrigation in the afternoon.

00:23:06.160 --> 00:23:10.597
So this is an astonishing
set of pictures, I think.

00:23:10.597 --> 00:23:12.180
So when you take
that and translate it

00:23:12.180 --> 00:23:13.480
I call it solar orchards.

00:23:13.480 --> 00:23:15.120
It's a form of silviculture.

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:17.670
Here's a building we designed
for the Netherlands that

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:21.900
can produce more energy than
it needs to operate and purify

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:22.800
it's own water.

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:27.374
And it has a budget the same
as a normal office building.

00:23:27.374 --> 00:23:28.290
So what is good water?

00:23:28.290 --> 00:23:30.190
Good water is clean
and it's available.

00:23:30.190 --> 00:23:31.620
It's a human right.

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:34.910
So the idea is not just, can
I take out some of the lead.

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:37.660
The idea is, every child should
have clean healthy water.

00:23:37.660 --> 00:23:39.970
So we've designed textiles
where the water coming

00:23:39.970 --> 00:23:41.700
into the factory
comes out clean--

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:43.116
clean enough to
drink, which means

00:23:43.116 --> 00:23:44.940
you'd rather use it
again, which means

00:23:44.940 --> 00:23:47.315
you don't have any water coming
out, because all you lose

00:23:47.315 --> 00:23:48.090
is evaporation.

00:23:48.090 --> 00:23:50.190
So all of a sudden we
realized that our factories

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:51.900
can be purification rituals.

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:54.630
This is the world's largest
green roof, the [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:56.400
for Ford Motor Company.

00:23:56.400 --> 00:23:59.340
This is, I don't know,
12, 15 years ago.

00:23:59.340 --> 00:24:01.860
And we used this to
purify all the water

00:24:01.860 --> 00:24:04.500
on the site instead of chemical
treatment plants and pipes.

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:08.700
And it's saved $435
million day one, CAPEX.

00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:11.010
Which with the Taurus
at a 4% margin,

00:24:11.010 --> 00:24:12.960
is the equivalent of
walking into the board

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:16.920
and giving them an order for
$900 million worth of cars.

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:18.900
The world's largest green roof.

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:22.740
So this is a drawing of a
factory by me as a 10-year-old.

00:24:22.740 --> 00:24:25.530
And on the left, this is what
you look at for a factory,

00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:28.270
and on the right is what we'd
like to look at for the future.

00:24:28.270 --> 00:24:31.740
So this is our factory for
Method under construction.

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:33.450
And it's got the
largest greenhouses

00:24:33.450 --> 00:24:35.310
on a building in the world now.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:36.940
It's what I've been told.

00:24:36.940 --> 00:24:39.780
And it's a factory that's wind
powered and solar powered.

00:24:39.780 --> 00:24:41.640
And the great thing
about something

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:46.330
like this-- imagine a child
in Pullman in Chicago,

00:24:46.330 --> 00:24:48.480
and when you ask them,
what is a factory, instead

00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:52.595
of drawing a thing with smoke
coming out it, they draw this.

00:24:52.595 --> 00:24:53.970
They draw things
that are growing

00:24:53.970 --> 00:24:55.080
food for their neighbor.

00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:56.370
It's a food desert there.

00:24:56.370 --> 00:24:58.180
They don't have fresh food.

00:24:58.180 --> 00:25:00.820
And so now they have
jobs making fresh food.

00:25:00.820 --> 00:25:03.240
This is part of what it
means to have a good life--

00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:05.917
safe, dignified for your kids.

00:25:05.917 --> 00:25:07.500
And we could actually
design all kinds

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:08.833
of strange and wonderful things.

00:25:08.833 --> 00:25:10.380
This is a factory
in India we did,

00:25:10.380 --> 00:25:12.570
where we put all the structure
on the outside of the building

00:25:12.570 --> 00:25:14.620
to keep it out of the
factories so it's clean.

00:25:14.620 --> 00:25:16.020
But we can do all
these different things

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:16.853
with this structure.

00:25:16.853 --> 00:25:18.870
We can grow food up there.

00:25:18.870 --> 00:25:20.610
We have solar
collectors up there.

00:25:20.610 --> 00:25:21.660
We have jobs up there.

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:23.910
So you're not only in
the factory making jobs.

00:25:23.910 --> 00:25:26.910
This is our first
tomato right here.

00:25:26.910 --> 00:25:28.770
Here it is.

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:31.620
The families can grow their
organic food here, as well as

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:34.580
work here in the sunshine.

00:25:34.580 --> 00:25:37.240
Now this is the idea of sharing.

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:39.720
And I just want
to show this man.

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:40.940
His name was Venkataswamy.

00:25:40.940 --> 00:25:42.780
He died, I don't know,
five years ago now.

00:25:42.780 --> 00:25:44.840
A cataract surgeon--
but he said,

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:47.210
why is it $1,900 to
get your eyesight back

00:25:47.210 --> 00:25:48.570
when you're 80-years-old?

00:25:48.570 --> 00:25:52.260
I can do it in 10 minutes.

00:25:52.260 --> 00:25:55.330
All I need is a cubic meter
of sterility and one scalpel.

00:25:55.330 --> 00:25:58.070
And this interocular
lens is $200.

00:25:58.070 --> 00:25:58.890
Why is it $200?

00:25:58.890 --> 00:26:00.770
We have contact lenses
that are disposal.

00:26:00.770 --> 00:26:02.840
Why is this $200 each?

00:26:02.840 --> 00:26:04.460
And we have blind people.

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:08.180
And I can give them back
eyesight in 10 minutes.

00:26:08.180 --> 00:26:10.710
So he said, what if I
gave it away for free?

00:26:10.710 --> 00:26:13.550
I could go to scale, because
I could have my own factories.

00:26:13.550 --> 00:26:15.900
And then we'd see what it
costs for the rich people.

00:26:15.900 --> 00:26:18.620
Anyway, when he died, he'd
given eyesight to three million

00:26:18.620 --> 00:26:20.270
people for free--

00:26:20.270 --> 00:26:23.210
three million people for free.

00:26:23.210 --> 00:26:25.680
And the people who could
afford it had to pay $50.

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:27.860
And he had seven hospitals.

00:26:27.860 --> 00:26:32.120
He built the business to
become immensely successful

00:26:32.120 --> 00:26:34.790
by collapsing the price for
those who could afford it,

00:26:34.790 --> 00:26:37.090
and everyone else
gets it for free.

00:26:37.090 --> 00:26:39.560
And because they
get it for free,

00:26:39.560 --> 00:26:41.060
the other people
could afford it.

00:26:41.060 --> 00:26:42.680
I mean, think about that.

00:26:42.680 --> 00:26:45.630
So the model becomes
a different question.

00:26:45.630 --> 00:26:50.390
We change the question of
statistical significance

00:26:50.390 --> 00:26:53.540
from, how much can I get
for how little I give,

00:26:53.540 --> 00:26:56.630
the question of modern
commerce, to how much

00:26:56.630 --> 00:27:00.050
can we give for all that we get?

00:27:00.050 --> 00:27:06.882
We move from limits and greed
to abundance and sharing.

00:27:06.882 --> 00:27:08.364
Thank you.

00:27:08.364 --> 00:27:11.822
