00:27:56.240 --> 00:27:58.930
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: It
comes back to children.

00:27:58.930 --> 00:28:03.380
In the Irish tradition,
in ancient Irish tradition

00:28:03.380 --> 00:28:06.290
there were five worlds and
the first was this one.

00:28:06.290 --> 00:28:09.885
And the second one is
called fairy, where the way

00:28:09.885 --> 00:28:12.260
they describe it it looks
exactly the same as this world,

00:28:12.260 --> 00:28:14.240
it's just a little bit better.

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:16.420
So I try and spend as much
time there as possible,

00:28:16.420 --> 00:28:19.010
because otherwise
you get depressed.

00:28:19.010 --> 00:28:21.130
But the third world
is called Tir Na Nog,

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:24.590
and it's the land of
the forever young.

00:28:24.590 --> 00:28:26.492
And people in this
world think that it

00:28:26.492 --> 00:28:27.950
might be nice to
be forever young--

00:28:27.950 --> 00:28:30.220
it's the Persephone myth.

00:28:30.220 --> 00:28:31.080
But it's underwater.

00:28:31.080 --> 00:28:32.270
It's in the umbrage.

00:28:32.270 --> 00:28:35.630
And the forever young
call us the immortals,

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:38.870
because we can have
children and they can't.

00:28:38.870 --> 00:28:39.860
That's interesting.

00:28:39.860 --> 00:28:42.200
And they're waiting
for Armageddon.

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:45.770
They're waiting for the shoe
to drop, boom, like that.

00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:49.020
So acting as if
you're forever young

00:28:49.020 --> 00:28:53.220
means you get this sort
of pathos and this fear

00:28:53.220 --> 00:28:55.530
that all of a sudden things
will end in an instant

00:28:55.530 --> 00:28:58.420
because you're forever young.

00:28:58.420 --> 00:29:00.740
And I think that
issue for me, if you

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:03.700
look at what happened
with the nuclear bomb

00:29:03.700 --> 00:29:06.980
in the middle of
the last century,

00:29:06.980 --> 00:29:08.870
after that point people
started living as

00:29:08.870 --> 00:29:11.650
if there might be no tomorrow.

00:29:11.650 --> 00:29:15.030
So we started creating
planned obsolescence.

00:29:15.030 --> 00:29:19.380
Party up, because there
might be no world tomorrow.

00:29:19.380 --> 00:29:21.870
So what difference does it
make if you use lots of paper?

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:24.522
The world might end in a moment.

00:29:24.522 --> 00:29:25.980
And so I think
we've started living

00:29:25.980 --> 00:29:27.063
as if there's no tomorrow.

00:29:27.063 --> 00:29:28.920
We're acting as if
we're forever young.

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:32.400
And I think it's
starting to haunt us now,

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:37.080
because we see both what happens
because we think that way,

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:38.580
on a day to day basis.

00:29:38.580 --> 00:29:41.130
But also we started
doing design-- we

00:29:41.130 --> 00:29:42.600
call it design for end of life.

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:43.980
I mean, really?

00:29:43.980 --> 00:29:46.710
Design for end of life--
if design is intention,

00:29:46.710 --> 00:29:49.211
is our intention to end life?

00:29:49.211 --> 00:29:49.710
You know?

00:29:49.710 --> 00:29:51.680
What if we are successful?

00:29:51.680 --> 00:29:52.410
Oh no.

00:29:52.410 --> 00:29:56.820
So we say design for
next use, instead of

00:29:56.820 --> 00:29:59.020
design for end of life.

00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:01.890
And once you say I'm
designing this for next use,

00:30:01.890 --> 00:30:05.230
then you don't look at
this and say, oh plastics.

00:30:05.230 --> 00:30:09.390
You go, oh, a durable
form of carbon.

00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:11.790
If I recycled that using
solar power and so on,

00:30:11.790 --> 00:30:14.280
I could use this over and over
again for many generations.

00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:18.480
This becomes an asset,
not a liability.

00:30:18.480 --> 00:30:21.230
So that's why I'm
always optimistic,

00:30:21.230 --> 00:30:25.870
because where everybody else
sees liabilities, I see assets.

00:30:25.870 --> 00:30:27.120
MARY DAVIDGE: And possibility.

00:30:27.120 --> 00:30:28.911
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: And
possibilities, yeah.

00:30:28.911 --> 00:30:32.070
MARY DAVIDGE: Bill,
who inspires you?

00:30:32.070 --> 00:30:34.350
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH:
Other than you?

00:30:34.350 --> 00:30:36.760
MARY DAVIDGE: Who inspires you?

00:30:36.760 --> 00:30:39.110
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: Well,
you do, that's for sure.

00:30:39.110 --> 00:30:40.860
When you look at what
you've accomplished,

00:30:40.860 --> 00:30:42.930
it's quite astonishing.

00:30:42.930 --> 00:30:46.180
My hero as a child was Gandhi.

00:30:46.180 --> 00:30:50.730
I was in Hong Kong, and
we were a British colony.

00:30:50.730 --> 00:30:53.540
And I thought the
questions he was asking

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:56.730
were really so critical,
and in a country where

00:30:56.730 --> 00:31:02.340
soil is the source
of all the relations.

00:31:02.340 --> 00:31:04.950
And when I became an architect--
and one of my first projects

00:31:04.950 --> 00:31:12.300
was to look if I could design
a Hindu temple for a Hindu

00:31:12.300 --> 00:31:13.830
community.

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:16.890
So I went to India for six
weeks and had a begging bowl

00:31:16.890 --> 00:31:21.730
and lived with a Hindu
community as a beggar.

00:31:21.730 --> 00:31:26.904
And I studied the shastras for
the design of Hindu temples

00:31:26.904 --> 00:31:29.070
and realized it was just
something I could never do,

00:31:29.070 --> 00:31:31.890
because you need to be inured
so deeply in the culture to do

00:31:31.890 --> 00:31:35.110
something that was meaningful.

00:31:35.110 --> 00:31:37.359
But the part that
really struck me

00:31:37.359 --> 00:31:39.150
was that in order to
build the Hindu temple

00:31:39.150 --> 00:31:42.240
you had to take,
usually a rocky spot,

00:31:42.240 --> 00:31:43.800
and then you had to
bring it to life.

00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:47.030
You had a three year protocol
to create fecundity there.

00:31:47.030 --> 00:31:51.220
You had to make it healthy
and full of food and benefit--

00:31:51.220 --> 00:31:52.140
flowers.

00:31:52.140 --> 00:31:53.370
It was amazing.

00:31:53.370 --> 00:31:54.910
It's a very prescribed process.

00:31:54.910 --> 00:31:57.060
And then you give the
soil that you just

00:31:57.060 --> 00:32:02.890
made from the sun and the rocks
and the air and the water,

00:32:02.890 --> 00:32:05.820
fecundity, growth,
and then you give that

00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:09.549
to the farmers around
it and build the temple.

00:32:09.549 --> 00:32:11.673
The temple has to be built
on a place that's alive.

00:32:11.673 --> 00:32:13.770
Isn't that beautiful?

00:32:13.770 --> 00:32:17.840
So I found that to be something
I like to do as a ritual.

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:19.800
I think it's an important idea.

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:21.990
And when I was at the
Museum of Natural History

00:32:21.990 --> 00:32:25.080
here, in the rotunda on
the way into the Hall

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:28.110
of the African peoples
they have this quote.

00:32:28.110 --> 00:32:31.720
And I looked it up
online later saying, wow,

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:34.335
who's Galla It was
attributed to Galla.

00:32:34.335 --> 00:32:36.360
I said, is this
some kind of Latin?

00:32:36.360 --> 00:32:37.170
What is this?

00:32:37.170 --> 00:32:42.720
And Galla was a subtribe
of the Oromo in Ethiopia.

00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:44.490
And the poem which
they then state

00:32:44.490 --> 00:32:47.830
is like, nobody knows
what this means.

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:50.450
Here's the poem.

00:32:50.450 --> 00:32:52.770
"One is born.

00:32:52.770 --> 00:32:54.870
One dies.

00:32:54.870 --> 00:32:57.423
The land increases."

00:32:57.423 --> 00:32:58.836
That's the poem.

00:33:01.591 --> 00:33:02.340
What does it mean?

00:33:04.850 --> 00:33:07.970
The world gets better
because we're here.

00:33:07.970 --> 00:33:10.110
Biology.

00:33:10.110 --> 00:33:11.690
One is born, one dies.

00:33:11.690 --> 00:33:13.200
It's the soil increases.

00:33:16.650 --> 00:33:19.265
So that's why I'm optimistic.

00:33:19.265 --> 00:33:20.390
MARY DAVIDGE: That's great.

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:23.450
So I have one more, and then
anyone who wants-- oh, we've

00:33:23.450 --> 00:33:24.320
got a question here.

00:33:24.320 --> 00:33:24.820
OK.

00:33:24.820 --> 00:33:25.900
I'll hold mine.

00:33:25.900 --> 00:33:27.100
Yes.

00:33:27.100 --> 00:33:28.060
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:33:28.060 --> 00:33:32.870
A question-- I wonder
what are your thoughts

00:33:32.870 --> 00:33:37.760
about the main
obstacles from using

00:33:37.760 --> 00:33:40.420
the new energy like
solar, nuclear,

00:33:40.420 --> 00:33:45.340
wind from being our
main source of power?

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:49.534
Is there anything stopping--
or what can we do?

00:33:49.534 --> 00:33:51.450
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: Let
me repeat the question.

00:33:54.070 --> 00:33:55.850
If I get it wrong, let me know.

00:33:55.850 --> 00:34:01.410
It's, what is the main obstacle
between us using solar, wind,

00:34:01.410 --> 00:34:04.620
and other forms of clean power
from the conventional practice

00:34:04.620 --> 00:34:06.150
we have now.

00:34:06.150 --> 00:34:09.550
I think it's very
straightforward really.

00:34:09.550 --> 00:34:12.870
It's the incumbency
of existing actors.

00:34:12.870 --> 00:34:14.976
People become
positionally conservative,

00:34:14.976 --> 00:34:16.350
because that's
what they're doing

00:34:16.350 --> 00:34:18.016
and that's what they
want to keep doing,

00:34:18.016 --> 00:34:20.370
so they protect it at all costs.

00:34:20.370 --> 00:34:23.010
So that's what
you're up against.

00:34:23.010 --> 00:34:25.320
What you're coming
in with, which

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:33.530
are what I would call them the
tools of waging peace, are--

00:34:33.530 --> 00:34:36.449
we have the things that
don't require regulation,

00:34:36.449 --> 00:34:39.389
because typically these
are relatively safe.

00:34:39.389 --> 00:34:40.949
In the case of
solar and wind they

00:34:40.949 --> 00:34:42.429
provide an immense
number of jobs.

00:34:42.429 --> 00:34:44.940
So we can argue
that one, for sure.

00:34:44.940 --> 00:34:47.760
And the price has collapsed
in the case of solar

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:50.290
because the commoditization
of solar collectors, which

00:34:50.290 --> 00:34:52.989
have had a bit of a
rough and tumble road

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:58.215
with a dramatic moment with
the Chinese dumping solar

00:34:58.215 --> 00:34:58.840
into the world.

00:34:58.840 --> 00:35:00.420
So it's caused a bit of a shock.

00:35:00.420 --> 00:35:03.000
But it's all part
of the collapse

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:04.990
of the cost of these things.

00:35:04.990 --> 00:35:06.960
So in the end, I
think the economics

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:08.760
are going to be the key driver.

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:11.490
So when President Trump
says we want to bring back

00:35:11.490 --> 00:35:15.570
all the jobs in coal, the
language might want to be,

00:35:15.570 --> 00:35:18.687
and as I think it will play
out, when you look at the coal

00:35:18.687 --> 00:35:21.270
companies and some of the other
facilities they're developing,

00:35:21.270 --> 00:35:23.550
even in West Virginia,
it's interesting to note

00:35:23.550 --> 00:35:28.210
they're solar-powered
because it's cost effective.

00:35:28.210 --> 00:35:30.360
And when you think about
it it's quite astonishing.

00:35:30.360 --> 00:35:33.945
We're seeing solar energy in
West Virginia at about 4.7

00:35:33.945 --> 00:35:35.550
cents a kilowatt hour.

00:35:35.550 --> 00:35:38.610
Well that's the same price as
buying coal-fired electricity.

00:35:38.610 --> 00:35:40.800
So the economics are coming.

00:35:40.800 --> 00:35:42.570
And I think it's really
the job creation.

00:35:42.570 --> 00:35:44.820
Because there's going to be
a lot more jobs putting up

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:46.770
solar collections
in West Virginia

00:35:46.770 --> 00:35:51.210
than having big equipment
and tear off mountaintops.

00:35:51.210 --> 00:35:54.562
AUDIENCE: It's economic
coming only recently?

00:35:54.562 --> 00:35:55.520
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: Yes.

00:35:55.520 --> 00:35:59.090
It's quite recent in the
big picture of things.

00:35:59.090 --> 00:36:01.340
