00:46:58.340 --> 00:46:59.340
I can't talk on a phone.

00:46:59.340 --> 00:47:01.129
I have this bubbling
stream here.

00:47:01.129 --> 00:47:01.920
It's too beautiful.

00:47:01.920 --> 00:47:03.240
That kind of thing.

00:47:03.240 --> 00:47:06.060
Go out in the natural
world as much as you can.

00:47:06.060 --> 00:47:08.230
Celebrate your presence there.

00:47:08.230 --> 00:47:10.920
And that is part of, I
think, of the healing

00:47:10.920 --> 00:47:12.210
that goes on with us.

00:47:12.210 --> 00:47:17.850
Because even if you look at the
notion of our daily activities,

00:47:17.850 --> 00:47:21.690
there's this notion of sort
of the platonic purity of,

00:47:21.690 --> 00:47:25.350
the joy of beauty and truth
and the human imagination

00:47:25.350 --> 00:47:28.440
and with creativity,
an experience.

00:47:28.440 --> 00:47:31.080
That's really important.

00:47:31.080 --> 00:47:32.820
And I'm sure you
celebrate that every day

00:47:32.820 --> 00:47:35.550
when you have revelations
in your work and so on.

00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:38.790
Then there's this issue of how
do you act on wisdom, which

00:47:38.790 --> 00:47:40.740
is the Aristotelian question.

00:47:40.740 --> 00:47:44.670
If you know this beauty,
then how do you behave?

00:47:44.670 --> 00:47:46.470
What do you do?

00:47:46.470 --> 00:47:49.170
So it's essentially, how
do you get from your values

00:47:49.170 --> 00:47:51.844
to value creation every day?

00:47:51.844 --> 00:47:53.760
So if you live in the
world of value creation,

00:47:53.760 --> 00:47:57.450
like just money and number,
you can pound your way up

00:47:57.450 --> 00:48:01.350
through tactics and
strategies to goals,

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:04.620
but you can't get to your values
of what's right and wrong.

00:48:04.620 --> 00:48:05.994
You're in the world number, see.

00:48:05.994 --> 00:48:08.160
But if you start with your
values, what do you think

00:48:08.160 --> 00:48:09.120
is right and wrong?

00:48:09.120 --> 00:48:12.570
Live that, then develop a set
of principles to behave by that

00:48:12.570 --> 00:48:13.350
don't move.

00:48:13.350 --> 00:48:14.210
That's why I wrote
something called

00:48:14.210 --> 00:48:15.668
the, "Hannover
Principles," for us.

00:48:15.668 --> 00:48:17.920
These are design principles--
things that don't move.

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:23.100
Respect the relationship
between spirit and matter.

00:48:23.100 --> 00:48:26.640
Insist on the rights of
humanity and nature to co-exist.

00:48:26.640 --> 00:48:30.690
Eliminate the concept of waste.

00:48:30.690 --> 00:48:32.820
Respect the limitations
of human design.

00:48:32.820 --> 00:48:34.410
Be humble.

00:48:34.410 --> 00:48:37.080
If anybody has trouble with
humility, just know this,

00:48:37.080 --> 00:48:40.950
it took us 5,000 years to
put wheels on our luggage.

00:48:40.950 --> 00:48:43.860
We went to the moon before
we had wheels on our luggage.

00:48:43.860 --> 00:48:45.600
So we're not that smart.

00:48:45.600 --> 00:48:48.780
It took another 20 years to
put four wheels on our luggage.

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:50.480
But, you know, we're moving.

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:52.990
But have some humility here.

00:48:52.990 --> 00:48:56.250
Then you go to design
and you have visions.

00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:59.150
And we know that without
execution, visions

00:48:59.150 --> 00:49:00.840
are hallucinations.

00:49:00.840 --> 00:49:01.920
I live there.

00:49:01.920 --> 00:49:03.650
That's I do visions.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:06.100
I do that professionally.

00:49:06.100 --> 00:49:10.432
But I know that if they don't
get executed, they're not real.

00:49:10.432 --> 00:49:11.640
So then you go to your goals.

00:49:11.640 --> 00:49:12.990
Then you do your strategies.

00:49:12.990 --> 00:49:14.310
Then you do your tactics.

00:49:14.310 --> 00:49:16.230
Then you do the metrics.

00:49:16.230 --> 00:49:18.150
Then you show the value.

00:49:18.150 --> 00:49:20.190
Show the value last.

00:49:20.190 --> 00:49:22.570
Show your values first.

00:49:22.570 --> 00:49:24.340
Because as Peter
Drucker pointed out,

00:49:24.340 --> 00:49:27.720
it's a manager's job to be
efficient and do something

00:49:27.720 --> 00:49:31.350
the right way, but
it's the executives job

00:49:31.350 --> 00:49:34.530
to do the right thing.

00:49:34.530 --> 00:49:37.994
Because if you're in
the wrong business,

00:49:37.994 --> 00:49:39.660
it doesn't matter how
efficient you are.

00:49:39.660 --> 00:49:42.900
If you use Six Sigma
statistical perfection,

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:47.100
while you do the wrong thing,
you become perfectly wrong.

00:49:47.100 --> 00:49:51.380
So as a person, just try
to live with your values,

00:49:51.380 --> 00:49:53.160
and then exercise
them every day.

00:49:53.160 --> 00:49:56.900
And if you grow safe
healthy food for yourself,

00:49:56.900 --> 00:49:58.130
just try that.

00:49:58.130 --> 00:49:59.000
Watch what happens.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:00.580
Because you're doing
the right thing.

00:50:00.580 --> 00:50:02.330
And then you get all
caught up in doing it

00:50:02.330 --> 00:50:04.640
the right way, which is fun.

00:50:04.640 --> 00:50:09.010
Because it's a curious thing
to do, watch things grow.

00:50:09.010 --> 00:50:09.844
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:50:09.844 --> 00:50:11.426
MARY DAVIDGE: One
more quick question.

00:50:11.426 --> 00:50:11.926
Emily.

00:50:11.926 --> 00:50:12.551
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:50:12.551 --> 00:50:14.470
I think my question's
changed like 35 times

00:50:14.470 --> 00:50:16.044
since I've been standing here.

00:50:16.044 --> 00:50:18.460
I do sustainability here for
those of you that don't know.

00:50:18.460 --> 00:50:22.480
And waste initiative is
kind of our focus this year.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:25.480
So you talk a lot
about getting people

00:50:25.480 --> 00:50:28.089
to go back to their
values and really it's

00:50:28.089 --> 00:50:29.630
everybody that has
to think about it.

00:50:29.630 --> 00:50:33.160
So one of the things that we
did for Earth Week was set up

00:50:33.160 --> 00:50:36.250
a recyclables display that
I think you might have seen.

00:50:36.250 --> 00:50:38.130
Did you see it, anybody?

00:50:38.130 --> 00:50:38.980
The Commons?

00:50:38.980 --> 00:50:39.620
No?

00:50:39.620 --> 00:50:41.770
See, we did not
publicize that enough.

00:50:41.770 --> 00:50:45.400
But it was a massive container
that shows two separations.

00:50:45.400 --> 00:50:47.500
So one of them was clean
recyclables-- glass,

00:50:47.500 --> 00:50:49.780
metal, plastic that can
be recycled, and the other

00:50:49.780 --> 00:50:50.650
is dirty.

00:50:50.650 --> 00:50:54.086
So within this
stream, at this point

00:50:54.086 --> 00:50:56.710
we're working within the system
that we have in New York which,

00:50:56.710 --> 00:50:58.320
if it's not clean, it
doesn't get recycled,

00:50:58.320 --> 00:50:59.278
it ends up in landfill.

00:50:59.278 --> 00:51:00.910
We have incineration.

00:51:00.910 --> 00:51:02.440
It's terrible.

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:05.920
So trying to educate
people, especially

00:51:05.920 --> 00:51:09.670
in a city that moves so fast
and is so based on disposable--

00:51:09.670 --> 00:51:14.020
how do you try to bring
that to people's attention?

00:51:14.020 --> 00:51:17.440
I mean, I've tried in, obviously
gloom and doom kind of ways,

00:51:17.440 --> 00:51:20.170
like look at how
much waste there is.

00:51:20.170 --> 00:51:22.450
Drop the Box campaign,
so that people

00:51:22.450 --> 00:51:25.060
use a plate instead of a
disposable-- those kinds

00:51:25.060 --> 00:51:25.970
of things.

00:51:25.970 --> 00:51:29.504
And it seems to be something
that people care about when

00:51:29.504 --> 00:51:30.670
you talk to them one on one.

00:51:30.670 --> 00:51:35.290
But in masses it's difficult
to get it to catch on.

00:51:35.290 --> 00:51:39.589
So how do you suggest that
we get more people involved

00:51:39.589 --> 00:51:40.630
in those kinds of things?

00:51:43.420 --> 00:51:46.510
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: It is
one of the great questions.

00:51:46.510 --> 00:51:51.070
I was saddened to hear
recently that the tourists who

00:51:51.070 --> 00:51:56.320
went to Bali to see some
exquisite tropical place

00:51:56.320 --> 00:52:00.160
with a culture that
was gracious and gentle

00:52:00.160 --> 00:52:04.570
are not going now because the
beaches are covered in plastic.

00:52:04.570 --> 00:52:07.300
And if you look at
the history of Bali,

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:13.100
it's only been one generation
from when they used leaves

00:52:13.100 --> 00:52:17.450
for plates, and they
ate with their hands.

00:52:17.450 --> 00:52:19.697
So it used to be you went
there and you got a plate,

00:52:19.697 --> 00:52:21.530
and when you're finished
with the plate it's

00:52:21.530 --> 00:52:23.330
what we call soil compostable.

00:52:23.330 --> 00:52:25.490
It was like ba.

00:52:25.490 --> 00:52:29.862
So a world where
littering is fun,

00:52:29.862 --> 00:52:31.070
and it goes back to the soil.

00:52:31.070 --> 00:52:32.280
Oh my goodness.

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:34.820
So I think we should
learn from that.

00:52:34.820 --> 00:52:37.490
And if we can start to imagine
that all of this detritus

00:52:37.490 --> 00:52:41.720
we have becomes
exquisitely designed

00:52:41.720 --> 00:52:45.110
to go back to cycles so people
can go on with their lives,

00:52:45.110 --> 00:52:47.530
and littering is fun.

00:52:47.530 --> 00:52:50.450
See right now I'm looking
at these giant projects

00:52:50.450 --> 00:52:53.390
for how to do road maps for
packaging as well as designing

00:52:53.390 --> 00:52:55.070
buildings and products.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:58.190
And part of what I'm trying
to figure out how to do

00:52:58.190 --> 00:53:00.420
is make it fun.

00:53:00.420 --> 00:53:04.400
So please litter
becomes like, huh?

00:53:04.400 --> 00:53:08.800
So right now I'm working
on e-commerce packaging

00:53:08.800 --> 00:53:13.489
that is all based on soil health
and just for the fun of it.

00:53:13.489 --> 00:53:15.530
So that getting e-commerce,
instead of it as some

00:53:15.530 --> 00:53:19.820
terrifying hybridization
of strange packaging--

00:53:19.820 --> 00:53:21.850
I don't know what you've seen.

00:53:21.850 --> 00:53:25.340
But you get boxes this big
with little things and bubbles

00:53:25.340 --> 00:53:26.100
and plastic.

00:53:26.100 --> 00:53:29.750
It's like the whole thing
just shows how insane it is.

00:53:29.750 --> 00:53:32.330
So I think it's a
big design problem.

00:53:32.330 --> 00:53:35.000
When I asked Ron Gonen when
he was the deputy commissioner

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:38.570
of sanitation for
New York if I could

00:53:38.570 --> 00:53:41.900
solve one problem for
him, what would it be?

00:53:41.900 --> 00:53:43.640
See they've built
composters now.

00:53:43.640 --> 00:53:47.570
So they are taking combustibles
in New York and composting.

00:53:47.570 --> 00:53:52.220
But they can't see the cup that
you're using here for water.

00:53:52.220 --> 00:53:54.800
We just had some water in a cup.

00:53:54.800 --> 00:53:56.690
AUDIENCE: They're
flaring the gas.

00:53:56.690 --> 00:53:57.650
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: And
they'll flare the gas

00:53:57.650 --> 00:53:58.691
that comes from all that.

00:53:58.691 --> 00:53:59.540
Yeah, exactly.

00:53:59.540 --> 00:54:01.535
So it's suboptimal.

00:54:01.535 --> 00:54:04.160
And so I think we need a marking
system for all these materials

00:54:04.160 --> 00:54:05.600
that we can see.

00:54:05.600 --> 00:54:07.880
And it probably has to be
optical so we can see it

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:11.090
anywhere-- that it can be done
by humans with two optical

00:54:11.090 --> 00:54:12.410
sensors her--

00:54:12.410 --> 00:54:16.460
very sophisticated,
and our robotic 3-D

00:54:16.460 --> 00:54:19.610
articulated elements.

00:54:19.610 --> 00:54:21.832
So I think we need
a marking system,

00:54:21.832 --> 00:54:24.290
and I think we need to make
this into something exquisitely

00:54:24.290 --> 00:54:25.250
beautiful.

00:54:25.250 --> 00:54:29.150
So we celebrate this instead
of saying minimize, avoid,

00:54:29.150 --> 00:54:31.940
reduce waste and
feel guilty, we say,

00:54:31.940 --> 00:54:36.650
eliminate the concept
of waste by design so

00:54:36.650 --> 00:54:40.220
that you can
celebrate, optimize,

00:54:40.220 --> 00:54:45.080
and share the joy of packaging.

00:54:45.080 --> 00:54:50.550
When I was a kid in Japan,
the package was the gift.

00:54:50.550 --> 00:54:52.974
How you ever seen
packaging in Japan?

00:54:52.974 --> 00:54:53.970
Oh.

00:54:53.970 --> 00:54:56.350
People will give you a gift
and it was so much fun.

00:54:56.350 --> 00:54:57.320
You'd unfold it.

00:54:57.320 --> 00:54:59.090
It was origami.

00:54:59.090 --> 00:55:01.910
You'd have a silk
scarf, you know.

00:55:01.910 --> 00:55:05.265
And then the question became,
who got the silk scarf?

00:55:05.265 --> 00:55:08.540
Do you give it back, cause
they can use it again

00:55:08.540 --> 00:55:11.120
or do you get to keep it
and use it for another gift?

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:14.810
I mean, it's a whole culture.

00:55:14.810 --> 00:55:20.014
Eggs came in rice straw,
braided rice straw.

00:55:20.014 --> 00:55:22.790
AUDIENCE: I'll have to talk to
some of the sourcing people.

00:55:22.790 --> 00:55:23.160
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: Yeah.

00:55:23.160 --> 00:55:24.270
But his biggest problem--

00:55:24.270 --> 00:55:26.940
Ron's biggest problem
he said was hamburger.

00:55:26.940 --> 00:55:31.500
A hamburger, an old hamburger
sitting in a plastic film

00:55:31.500 --> 00:55:33.720
in a foam tray.

00:55:33.720 --> 00:55:37.000
There was absolutely nothing
he could do with that.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:39.519
And that starts to send
the signals that we're

00:55:39.519 --> 00:55:42.060
going to have to do a lot more
things that are biodegradable,

00:55:42.060 --> 00:55:45.360
compostable coherently all
the way to the molecules,

00:55:45.360 --> 00:55:48.486
not into tiny bits of
plastic, which we see today.

00:55:48.486 --> 00:55:51.380
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the
zero waste by 2030--

00:55:51.380 --> 00:55:54.280
I sat in a group that asked
the organizations what

00:55:54.280 --> 00:55:58.480
they'd done so far and
nobody had an answer yet.

00:55:58.480 --> 00:56:00.250
So, we'll see.

00:56:00.250 --> 00:56:01.152
Optimism.

00:56:01.152 --> 00:56:02.110
MARY DAVIDGE: Optimism.

00:56:02.110 --> 00:56:04.230
You can be like
Bill, never give up.

00:56:04.230 --> 00:56:05.230
WILLIAM MCDONOUGH: Yeah.

00:56:05.230 --> 00:56:06.530
Persistence.

00:56:06.530 --> 00:56:08.710
MARY DAVIDGE: Persistence.

